We need to assess whether visualization described is misleading. The description: line chart with y-axis 0 to 14,000,000, showing recovered up to ~12.6M and active ~1.68M. Claims that recovered line upward faster than active line, implying situation improving. Potential issues: The y-axis starts at 0? It says ranging from 0 to 14,000,000, so not truncated. But maybe scale is linear; difference between recovered and active is huge, making active line appear relatively flat. Could be misleading by emphasizing gap but not showing total cases (including deaths). Could be cherry-picking: focusing only on recovered vs active, omitting deaths and total cases, giving impression of improvement. Also could be incomplete: not showing daily new cases, surge wave (second wave). But the chart's time includes April 2021, which includes second wave in India. The active cases may have risen sharply in March/April 2021. The description says active line upward slower; maybe misreading: Actually active cases peaked ~3 million around May 2021 (but up to April 17 maybe ~1.6M). So maybe the chart is accurate. However, the interpretation that recovery outpaces active growth may be misleading because active cases are a subset of total cases; the gap is large but not necessarily implying control; active cases can still be high relative to population.

Potential error types: Cherry-picking (only showing recovered vs active, ignoring deaths or total cases). Also maybe misleading framing via linguistic rhetoric: title "Increasing gap between COVID-19 Recovered & Active Cases" suggests improvement. Could be "Incorrect reading of chart": the author says active cases increase slower, but actually active cases may be increasing faster in proportion. But not enough evidence.

Truncated axis? No.

Dual axis? Not described.

Inappropriate encoding? Line chart for two cumulative totals is fine.

Unclear encoding? Probably fine.

Thus main issue: Cherry-picking, possibly Issues with data validity (no mention of deaths, testing rates). Also possibly Causal inference? No cause given.

So is it misleading? I'd say yes, due to cherry-picking and possibly framing that suggests improvement while ignoring rising active cases trend.

Confidence on misleading: maybe 75.

Intentional? Likely intentional to persuade postponement of exam. Could be moderate confidence 65.
